# bknr.datastore (knobo fork)

An in-memory, CLOS/MOP-based data store with transactions for Common Lisp.
Objects live in RAM and are made durable by a transaction log plus periodic
snapshots, so the whole object graph is queryable at memory speed and survives
restarts.

This is a **maintained fork** of [bknr-datastore/bknr-datastore][upstream] by
Hans Hübner. Upstream has [stopped accepting issues and pull requests][monument]
and is kept as a "monument of better times"; some documentation is still linked
from the [original web site](https://bknr.common-lisp.dev/). This fork continues
development — chiefly a replication module (below) — and exists precisely because
upstream invited people to "create your own" fork.

> This fork is developed largely with AI assistance — see [About this fork](#about-this-fork).

## About this fork

- **It is largely AI-assisted.** Most of the code here is written with the help
  of LLM tooling, with a human reviewing, testing and steering. That is a
  deliberate choice, and the opposite of upstream's stance; if you prefer
  human-authored Common Lisp, the [upstream repository][upstream] is the place
  to read.
- **It aims to stay tested and honest.** Changes come with tests (a FiveAM unit
  suite and a two-process integration suite), and docstrings explain *why* a
  thing is done, not just what it does.
- **The core datastore is unchanged in spirit.** The fork adds on top rather
  than rewriting; existing bknr.datastore code and behaviour are preserved.

## What this fork adds

### Replication (`bknr.datastore.replication`)

Log-shipping replication: a **primary** ships its committed transactions to one
or more **standby** replicas, which apply them and stay in lockstep.

- **Transport-agnostic apply core.** The same `apply-replication-stream` drives
  an in-memory pipe, a file tail, or a socket; the TCP layer is thin on top.
- **Bootstrap + resume.** A fresh or stale replica is bootstrapped with the
  primary's full current state; a returning replica resumes from its last LSN
  and receives only the delta, falling back to a bootstrap when the primary's
  identity (epoch) changed or a snapshot rotated the needed log away.
- **Non-blocking fan-out.** Per-replica writer threads with bounded send queues:
  a slow replica is dropped rather than allowed to stall the primary's commits,
  and the large base transfer runs off the commit lock.
- **Apply hooks.** `add-apply-observer` is the replica-side counterpart of a
  commit observer — use it for server-sent events, derived/materialized views,
  or change-data-capture.
- **Mutual authentication.** A shared secret gates replication via a nonce-based
  HMAC-SHA256 challenge-response; the secret never crosses the wire.
- **Optional TLS** via the separate `bknr.datastore.replication/tls` system
  (cl+ssl), so the base module carries no OpenSSL dependency.

Design and rationale: [`doc/replication-design.md`](doc/replication-design.md).

### Examples and tooling (`bin/`)

Everything under [`bin/`](bin/README.md) is **example and test code, not
production library code**:

- `bknr-repl.ros` — a runnable two-terminal demo of replication (a primary you
  type into, a standby that mirrors it live).
- `integration-test.exp` / `integration-test.sh` — the two-process integration
  suite; `smoke-test.sh` — a minimal end-to-end check.

These use [Roswell](https://github.com/roswell/roswell) (`ros`), the de-facto
Common Lisp script-runner and installer that much of the modern CL ecosystem
ships with, to launch a script or build it into a standalone binary. **The
library itself has no dependency on Roswell** — it is only how these examples
run themselves.

## Installing

Upstream is installable via [Quicklisp](http://quicklisp.org/) as
`bknr-datastore`. This fork is not in Quicklisp; load it from a checkout, e.g.
with [Roswell](https://github.com/roswell/roswell):

```sh
ros run --eval '(push #P"/path/to/bknr-datastore/src/" asdf:*central-registry*)' \
        --eval '(ql:quickload :bknr.datastore.replication)'
```

The replication module depends on `usocket`, `bordeaux-threads`, `ironclad` and
`trivial-utf-8`; the optional TLS system additionally needs `cl+ssl`.

## Running the tests

```sh
# core datastore + replication unit suites (FiveAM, via Roswell)
ros run --eval '(push #P"/path/to/bknr-datastore/src/" asdf:*central-registry*)' \
        --eval '(ql:quickload :bknr.datastore.replication/test)' \
        --eval '(asdf:test-system :bknr.datastore.replication)' --quit

# two-process integration suite (builds the demo binary first)
ros build bin/bknr-repl.ros
BKNR_REPL=./bin/bknr-repl expect bin/integration-test.exp
```

The integration suite drives a live primary and standby with [`expect`][expect],
waiting for real output markers instead of fixed sleeps. `bin/integration-test.sh`
is a thin wrapper that runs the same `.exp` script, so either invocation works.

